   <text xml:lang="en">
      <body>
         <div type="article">
            <head><title type="main"><hi rend="bold"><rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw"
                           >WOMAN 'CRUSOE'</persName></rs> LIVED <rs><date notBefore="1835"
                           notAfter="1853" cert="high">20 YEARS</date></rs> ON <rs><placeName
                           type="island" key="#i_sn">ISLAND</placeName></rs></hi></title></head>
            <byline><hi rend="bold">(By Science Service).</hi></byline>
            <dateline><placeName type="city" key="#ci_sm">SANTA MONICA,
               Cal.</placeName>&#8212;</dateline>
            <p><span type="trope" n="8">The story of <rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">a
                        woman "Robinson Crusoe"</persName></rs> who lived alone on <rs><placeName
                        type="island" key="#i_sn">an island</placeName></rs> for <rs><date
                        notBefore="1835" notAfter="1853" cert="high">twenty years</date></rs> is
                  told by <persName type="author" key="#rmo">Dr. Roy L. Moodie</persName>, who has
                  been delving into the records of old native life in <rs><placeName type="region"
                        key="#re_socalcoast">this region</placeName></rs> in his study of
                  prehistoric disease in <placeName type="country" key="#co_usa"
                  >America</placeName>.</span></p>
            <p><span type="trope" n="8"><rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">The feminine
                        Crusoe</persName></rs> had been a member of <rs><orgName
                        type="nativeamericantribes" key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">a small group of
                        Indians</orgName></rs> which lived on <placeName type="island" key="#i_sn"
                     >San Nicolas Island</placeName>, off the <placeName type="state" key="#st_cal"
                     >California</placeName> coast, about a hundred years ago.</span> The <persName
                  type="group" key="#misfats; #ndur; #aji">Spanish fathers</persName> persuaded
                  <persName type="group" key="#bhagroup">the group</persName> to leave
                     <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">their lonely island</placeName></rs>
               and find better protection at the <placeName type="mission" key="#mi_sb">Santa
                  Barbara Mission</placeName>. But <rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw"
                     >this woman</persName></rs> refused to come.</p>
            <p>All alone she demonstrated her self-sufficiency in the world by making her home of
               whale ribs and brush, and by living off the abundant fish, abalones, birds, seals,
               and some plant products. She made her clothing of bird skins. When at last she was
               brought to <rs><placeName type="mission" key="#mi_sb">the mission</placeName></rs>
               she died within six weeks.</p>
            <p><rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">The island</placeName></rs> possesses many
               relics of aboriginal life, but none so romantic as the record of <rs><persName
                     type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">the lost woman</persName></rs>, <persName
                  type="author" key="#rmo">Dr. Moodie</persName> said.</p>
         </div>
